<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-218-936  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 218 936.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>TPT-Networking Management Magazine  April 1989 v7 n4 p24(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Getting fiber to the desktop: the first high-speed LAN to changethe role of fiber optics in office data communications is FDDI.andO;(local area network; Fiber Distributed Data Interface)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bender, Albert D.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The first high-speed fiber local area network (LAN) is FiberDistributed Data Interface (FDDI), a proposed American NationalStandards Institute (ANSI) standard (X.3T9.5).andP;  FDDI specifies a100M-bps token ring that uses fiber optic cabling.andP;  Five hundredstations up to two kilometers apart are supported, expanding to100 kilometers.andP;  This is an improvement of 10 to 100 times, inthroughput and area coverage, over current LANs.andP;  Other benefitsinclude reliability and fault tolerance.andP;  More important, FDDIrepresents a definitive solution to incompatibility problems amongfirst generation LANs.andP;  For users who foresee a need for fiber,guidelines for preparing for FDDI are presented.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber OpticsLocal Area NetworksOffice AutomationFiber Distributed Data Interface StandardStandardsNew Technique.andO;Feature:   illustrationcharttable.andO;Caption:   AN FDDI network. (chart)FDDI fault-tolerant capability. (chart)FDDI bridge selection criteria. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>